µC70:50µC2: There's a small "VIP" party for the winners, nominees, jury members and everyone who had something to do with the scene.org awards. People socialize and discuss the results, PS is once again the perfect butler, handing out the champaign and pretzels while Melwyn tries to find each nominee to give them their certificate (the winners have already received their little statue designed by Visualice).

µC73:0µC2: In dense clouds of smoke, the next concert kicks off: BASS plays various demo soundtracks, such as the State Of Mind soundtrack (original by Senser) and Onward from Dope/Complex. I didn't hear who the other members are but Sir Garbagetruck is singing and Gargay/Conspiracy plays the drums. It doesn't sound bad, taken in account they only started practicing together 2 days ago :)

µC73:48µC2: They're followed by the Ultrasound concert, nice renditions of the Bubble Bobble theme, the Second Reality soundtrack and more. But since I've trouble staying awake I call it a day.

µC711:14µC2: Back awake from the seminar announcements :)

µC712:57µC2: The park outside is filled with sceners catching some sun, and someone's even cooking soup in a big kettle above the campfire.

µC715:05µC2: One downside of this location is the small amount of toilets, I'm tired of having to wait in the queue. On the other hand the orgos deserve kudos for replacing the garbage bags several times during the party (yes, I'm sitting at a corner next to one). And the compo threadmill starts for the second day! First one: streaming music!
13 entries, in a good mix of styles. I liked the stadium rock of Tonite Fairlite, the excellent vocals in Wir Gehen Voran and the melody of Inside Ruby.

µC715:58µC2: Sir Garbagetruck who has taken the place of Diver next to me has a mac mini with him, unfortunately he can't find an USB keyboard anywhere so he has to use the on-screen keyboard hack to type. After a while he runs Variform/Kewlers on it, yep on a Mac! Kewlers are appearently porting some of their older demos to the Mac, which is great IMHO!

The next compo is the C64 GFX, which will be won hands down by the fifth and last picture of wolves, titled Until It Sleep.

µC716:22µC2: And the oldskool version of the executable music compo starts: 32K programs only for CPUs with less then 32 bits. Most are quite chippy, of course, although "I love my 64" manages to include a voice sample, and "New kids on the boot block" actually runs from a boot sector on a disk!

µC717:09µC2: The 96K game compo has some literally shitty games, but also some jewels such as the clone of Lotus Turbo Challenge (the nostalgic audience went crazy with that), or Fist Of Fire, an colorful R-type sidescroller. The playable version of the lemmings-like Raving Tomatoes 4K is also quite cool.

The console/real wild has no GSM or PDA entries this year, but quite some gameboy entries, one Dreamcast demo with raytracing, a C64 port of the amiga demo Lapsuus, and a last-minute entry from Limp Ninja on the Xbox. But the major revelation was the Shizzle demo on the pokemini. It has only a low-res black&white lcd display and 512kb of flash, so they started with simple effects sych as vectorballs, a wormhole, tunnels etc (all so dithered it was hard to recognise them), but then a familiar scroller started "Another way to scroll", followed by a lens effect over a demon face... Yes, it's Second Reality for the pokemini! Up to and including the flight through the city. They finished with a move of a running girl (bouncy!) and the Xbox logo, above which was written "You can't do this on an..." :)

µC719:13µC2: There's a bit of a break in the schedule, and Metalvotze resumes screaming in their microphone. They've been playing some german dialogue which seems to be hilarious for those who understands it, Skyrunner clues me in: it's a famous prank-call of a radio host calling some shop to complain very rude about a broken appliance he bought there. One sample they play over and over again is "Hallo! Wass?!" (Hello? What?!), to the point everyone is so fed up with it it becomes funny. When the orgos want to say something, they announce "Hallo?" and the audience screamms back "Wass?!" :)

µC719:46µC2: The dangers of bored drunken sceners: naked wrestling on the frontstage (and bigscreen). Use your fantasy, at your own risk <shudder>. The orgos seems to be bored as well, and ask if anyone can lend them a wireless lan-cable.

µC720:13µC2: Finally the PC 64K starts! As with most executable compos, the orgos have already pre-sorted them more or less from bad to good. The two last ones are equally excellent: Binary Flow is the Assembly invitation intro from Conspiracy with beautiful Tron-like effects, and Death & Taxes from Fairlight is a theme-demo with very good design about a stick-figure walking between trees and a city of floating blocks. It's actually 64.5K big, but Fairlight gave the orgos a version without loading bar that fits inside the 64K limit.

The orgas decided to show the one with the loading bar and the audience agreed (with applause during the loading :))


µC721:20µC2: The amiga demo compo is slightly delayed, so the orgos show a special demo for a special scener on the bigscreen: Hete Dansactie! (This demo, made as a joke for Rob/Aardbei's birthday, has been submitted and unwittingly accepted at many parties for years, it's so bad most people instantly forget it.)

7 demos show that the Amiga scene is still alive, and the last 3 shall no doubt end up as the first 3. Multiverse/Loonies has the partyplace UFO, an infinite zoom, a robot carrying a lady in distress and other nice 3D scenes.

Glare/Mad Wizards has tons of 3D with plenty of glare (as the title warns), logos in an unreadable twirled font, and a kind of negative meta-ball scene made of cubes (hard to explain so go get the .avi). I didn't see any "we'll probably end 2nd again" remarks in it, like last year, but they could just as wel have added them:

The Black Lotus closes the compo with a killer demo, Ocean Machine. It has an M.C. Escher like floating city scene, a dancing balerina with ribbons flying behind her, greets brought with little hexagons and an amazing voxel tree-on-the-hilltop ending.

µC722:10µC2: Pornophonique, which are two guys with a guitar, a gameboy and a C64, repeat their performance from TUM*04 at Breakpoint, while ASCII videos are shown on the bigscreen. I recognise their Sad Sad Robot song (which is available for free on www.pornophonique.de), but the Britney Spears cover is new :/

µC722:58µC2: We've been warned: the PC demo compo will take very long (en will be great). All listeners of Nectarine (the scene internet radio) first get on stage to make a group picture, the orgos apologize for cutting 4 joke-demos, and then the mother  of all democompos starts.



µC0Sunday 27 March
µC0------------------
µC71:30µC2: 2 hours 30 minutes and 28(!) demos later, I can only say: 1) the limits on what a great demo can do have been pushed back again, and 2) I'll probably need to buy a new videocard :)

At demo 23, which was from Farbrausch, I thought the compo would probably be almost finished, but five at least as impressive demos followed.

Just some of the highlights: The Nonstop Schlachthaus Experience/Speckdrumm: Completely unrelated to the Nonstop Ibiza Experience! An extremely detailed and realistic 3D demo telling the dark story of a cows final destination. Very good animation as well.

Exodus Modus/Keyboarders: a theme demo with a little metal ball rolling along a yellow ribbon. Simple but stylish.

155/95/Plastic: During one part (the closeup of the wasp) I thought for a moment a video was playing! Very, very good 3D, probably making heavy use of shaders. It may be a simple object show (not much animation), but it looks sooo pretty and shiny!

Aether/MFX : Lovely fire and ice-based effects, with a majestic solar system scene. There were also a lot of invitation demos with varying quality, but I was rather disappointed by Aphorism for the masses from ASD, it's a noisy techno-demo with RGB-shifted visuals. It's very different from Planet Risk and it's not my taste :(

Next it's voting time, I go exchange my wristband at the infodesk to get a votekey, open my notes and start to vote. Just like at Assembly, the voting page shows little thumbnails of the pictures, intros and demos. It's nice to see that the orgos just keep on improving the party.

µC73:17µC2: Plenty of people are leaving already. I'm not sure if it's caused by the lesser amount of heat-producing PCs but it's way colder than the previous nights. Djefke wants to leave the partyplace tomorrow before the prize ceremony, but I doubt he'll wake up in time :)

µC79:54µC2: The bigscreen subtly urges everyone to vote: "NOW OR NEVER: VOTE FUCKING NOW", as the deadline is 10 o'clock.

µC710:14µC2: Oops, seems like someones car has troubles starting: the bigscreen is asking for a car-mechanic :) After the fast-compo which had 15 entries of mixed quality (including one running in MS Word!), Djefke wakes up enough to depart. The trip back was uneventful, and I was asleep most of the time.

I had mixed feelings about moving the partyplace, but like everyone else whom I talked to I feel it's a change for the better: it's warmer, larger, has room for a huge bigscreen, there's a tribune to watch the compos, a seminar room,... Only the amount of toilets is a bad point. The organising was excellent with almost no delays in the schedule, lots of small improvements, the new seminars,...

And last but not least the audience was great,  the atmosphere at Breakpoint is really nice and friendly, and some incredible good productions were released. I'm already looking forward to next year!
